# Git-jenkins integration means:
# Jenkins should be able to:
# Pull code from Git repo
# Trigger builds automatically on code changes
# Work securely using credentials

# Git integration with Jenkins allows Jenkins to pull source code and trigger builds automatically using webhooks or polling. 
# Authentication is handled using credentials like SSH keys or tokens.”

# Types of Integration:
# Type	          Description
# Poll SCM	     Jenkins checks repo periodically
# Webhook	       Git triggers Jenkins instantly

# In real projects → Webhook is used

Step-by-Step Setup

Step 1: Install Git in Jenkins server
sudo apt install git -y
git --version

Step 2: Configure Git in Jenkins
Go to Manage Jenkins → Global Tool Configuration
Add:Name: git & Path: /usr/bin/git

Step 3: Add Credentials (IMPORTANT)
Go to Manage Jenkins → Credentials → Global → Add Credentials
For HTTPS:
Username + Password / Token
For SSH (Recommended 🔥):
Kind: SSH Username with private key

If you are taking the git code as SSH Then please implement the below step or else skip if you are using HTTPS

Step 4: Setup SSH (Best Practice)
On Jenkins server:
ssh-keygen
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
Copy key → add to Git (GitHub/GitLab): Settings → SSH Keys

Step 5: Create Jenkins Job
1. freestyle Job or Pipeline Job
